      \Pi _f m\ar [r]\ar [d]\ar [dr, phantom, "\lrcorner ", very near start] & c\xrightarrow {m}x\xrightarrow {f}y^{(x\xrightarrow {f}y)}\ar [d] \\
      1_y\ar [r, "1_f^\dag "'] & x\xrightarrow {f} y^{(x\xrightarrow {f} y)}\makebox [0pt][l]{,}
    \end {tikzcd}


 with action on morphisms induced by functoriality of the
  pullback.

The construction of the bijection now demands that, for c\in  C, r\in    Rc, and p\in  Pc, we have \alpha _c(r, p) = \operatorname {ev}_c(\beta _c(r), p) =   \beta _c(r)_c(1_c, p). This defines \beta _c(r)_c, and naturality in C
  now forces, for any c\xrightarrow {f} d, 




